  <!-- Your Document Checklist -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Your Document Checklist</h2>
      <p>These are the documents you need to prepare. Your employer or their PRO will tell you what to bring, but having everything ready in advance prevents delays.</p>

      <h3>Documents You Provide</h3>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Passport</strong> — minimum 6 months validity remaining. MOHRE's system blocks applications where the passport expires within 6 months.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/personal/academic/degree/">Degree certificate</a></strong> — attested through the full chain, then translated to Arabic if not in English or Arabic</li>
        <li><strong>Experience letters</strong> — from previous employers, translated if not in English or Arabic</li>
        <li><strong>Passport photographs</strong> — white background, recent</li>
        <li><strong>Any professional licenses</strong> — for regulated professions (healthcare, engineering, teaching)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Documents Your Employer Handles</h3>
      <ul class="checklist checklist--employer">
        <li><strong>Employment offer letter</strong> — must match the MOHRE standard contract format</li>
        <li><strong>MOHRE standard employment contract</strong> — dual-language Arabic + English</li>
        <li><strong>Company trade license</strong> — proving the business is authorized to hire</li>
        <li><strong>Establishment card</strong> — company's MOHRE registration</li>
        <li><strong>Quota approval</strong> — some company types have hiring limits</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-block callout-block--info">
        <h4>Documents You Do NOT Need to Translate</h4>
        <p>Passports, Emirates ID, and documents already in Arabic or English do not need translation. Your employer's trade license and establishment card are their responsibility. Only translate documents from your home country that are in other languages. Check our <a href="/resources/translation-type-decision-guide/">translation type guide</a> if unsure.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Process -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>The Work Permit Process: Your Part</h2>
      <p>MOHRE work permit applications go through Tasheel service centers. Your employer or their PRO submits everything. Here is what the process looks like from your side.</p>

      <div class="process-steps">
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="step-num">1</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h3>Attest Your Degree Certificate</h3>
            <p>Before anything else, your <a href="/personal/academic/degree/">degree certificate</a> must be attested. The chain depends on your home country.</p>
            <div class="path-grid">
              <div class="path-box">
                <h4>Hague Countries</h4>
                <p>India, Philippines, Bangladesh, USA, UK, Canada</p>
                <p>Notarize &rarr; Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</p>
              </div>
              <div class="path-box">
                <h4>Non-Hague Countries</h4>
                <p>Pakistan, Egypt, Syria, Jordan</p>
                <p>Home Ministry &rarr; Home MOFA &rarr; UAE Embassy &rarr; UAE MOFA</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>UAE MOFA <a href="/services/attestation/">attestation</a> costs AED 150 per document and takes 1-3 working days through the eDAS 2.0 system.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="step-num">2</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h3>Translate Non-English/Arabic Documents</h3>
            <p>After attestation, have your documents translated by an <a href="/legal-translation-dubai/">MOJ-certified translator</a>. Documents that typically need translation:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/personal/academic/degree/">Degree certificates</a> in Hindi, Urdu, Chinese, Filipino, Bengali, or other languages</li>
              <li>Experience letters from companies that issue in non-English languages</li>
              <li>Professional licenses from home country regulatory bodies</li>
              <li><a href="/personal/immigration/pcc/">Police clearance certificates</a> in non-English/Arabic</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Send documents via <a href="https://wa.me/971508620217">WhatsApp</a> and we confirm which ones need translation. Standard delivery is 24 hours; express is 2-4 hours.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="step-num">3</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h3>Give Documents to Your Employer</h3>
            <p>Provide all originals plus Arabic translations to your employer or their PRO. They compile the full package and submit through Tasheel.</p>
            <p>Common delays at this stage:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Employee waits for employer to ask instead of preparing proactively</li>
              <li>Employer assumes degree is already attested when it is not</li>
              <li>Documents are scattered between home country and UAE</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="step-num">4</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h3>MOHRE Eye AI Reviews Your Application</h3>
            <p>Since October 2025, MOHRE uses the "Eye" AI system for initial document review. This system uses Regula OCR and Azure AI Vision to verify:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Document authenticity (detecting alterations or forgeries)</li>
              <li>Completeness (all required documents present)</li>
              <li>Compliance (attestation chain intact, translations certified)</li>
              <li>Hard blocks: passport validity under 6 months, residency under 1 month</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The AI catches errors that human clerks sometimes missed. Blurry scans, missing attestation stamps, and unsigned translations are all flagged automatically.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="step-num">5</div>
          <div class="step-body">
            <h3>Work Permit Issued (or Nawakas)</h3>
            <p>If everything passes review, the work permit is issued within 5-10 working days.</p>
            <p>If something is missing or incorrect, your application enters <strong>Nawakas</strong> — MOHRE's process for handling deficient applications. The system identifies what is missing and provides a specific notification. Your employer must submit corrections through Tasheel.</p>
            <p>Nawakas is more informative than GDRFA rejections. MOHRE usually tells you what is wrong. But each correction cycle adds days to weeks.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Eye AI Section -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>What MOHRE's Eye AI System Actually Checks</h2>
      <p>Understanding what the automated system looks for helps you avoid triggering Nawakas delays.</p>

      <div class="check-grid">
        <div class="check-card">
          <div class="check-icon"><i class="fas fa-passport"></i></div>
          <h3>Passport Validity</h3>
          <p>Hard block if your passport expires within 6 months. The system will not even accept the application. Renew your passport before starting the process.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="check-card">
          <div class="check-icon"><i class="fas fa-stamp"></i></div>
          <h3>Attestation Chain</h3>
          <p>The AI verifies attestation stamps and stickers are present and legible. Missing or unclear MOFA attestation triggers a flag. Ensure your documents are attested before translation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="check-card">
          <div class="check-icon"><i class="fas fa-language"></i></div>
          <h3>Translation Certification</h3>
          <p>MOJ stamp, QR code, and translator license number must be visible. Non-certified translations or translations from unlicensed providers are flagged.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="check-card">
          <div class="check-icon"><i class="fas fa-graduation-cap"></i></div>
          <h3>Academic Documents</h3>
          <p>Degree must be clear and complete. Missing or unclear academic certificates are among the most common MOHRE rejection reasons. The degree title and university name must be readable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="check-card">
          <div class="check-icon"><i class="fas fa-image"></i></div>
          <h3>Document Quality</h3>
          <p>Blurry scans, cropped edges, and unreadable text are flagged. Submit clear, high-resolution scans. Phone photos of documents are risky — use a scanner when possible.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="check-card">
          <div class="check-icon"><i class="fas fa-user-check"></i></div>
          <h3>Name Consistency</h3>
          <p>Your name must match across all documents: passport, degree, experience letters, and translations. Transliteration variations (common in Arabic, Hindi, Urdu names) should be noted by the translator.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Common Rejection Reasons -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Most Common MOHRE Rejection Reasons</h2>
      <p>Based on MOHRE's published guidance and what we see from clients who need urgent retranslation after rejection.</p>

      <ol class="rejection-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Missing documents</strong>
          <p>The single most frequent cause. Usually a degree that was never submitted, or an experience letter that was forgotten. Use the checklist above.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Expired passport or residency</strong>
          <p>MOHRE's Eye system blocks these automatically. No human even reviews the application.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Missing or unclear academic certificates</strong>
          <p>Degrees that are blurry, partially cropped, or in a language the system cannot process. Always provide a clear scan plus the Arabic translation.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Job offer contradicts labor law</strong>
          <p>Employer issue, not yours. But it stalls the permit. The job title and description must match your qualifications and the company's licensed activities.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Occupation-to-business mismatch</strong>
          <p>Your job title must align with your employer's trade license activities. A restaurant cannot hire an "engineer" through MOHRE.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Company violations or quota exceeded</strong>
          <p>If your employer has unresolved labor violations or has exceeded their hiring quota, no new permits are issued. This is outside your control.</p>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>For a detailed look at document-related work permit rejections, read our <a href="/blog/mohre-work-permit-document-issues/">MOHRE rejection prevention guide</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Employment Contract Language -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Understanding the MOHRE Employment Contract</h2>
      <p>MOHRE mandates a standard employment contract format. Understanding its language requirements protects you.</p>

      <h3>Language Requirements</h3>
      <p>Every MOHRE standard employment contract is dual-language: <strong>Arabic and English</strong>. Since January 2016, a third language can be added for the worker's benefit:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Bengali, Chinese, Dari, Hindi, Malayalam</li>
        <li>Nepalese, Sinhalese, Tamil, Urdu</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The job offer letter must also be in Arabic, English, and a language the worker understands.</p>

      <div class="callout-block callout-block--warning">
        <h4>The Arabic Version Controls</h4>
        <p>In any dispute, the Arabic text of the employment contract is the legally binding version. If the English text contradicts the Arabic, the Arabic prevails. Make sure you understand both versions before signing. If your contract includes a <a href="/legal/contracts/lease/">lease agreement</a> or other supplementary documents, these may also require Arabic translation.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>What You Should Check</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Job title</strong> — matches your qualifications and the actual role</li>
        <li><strong>Salary</strong> — matches the offer letter exactly</li>
        <li><strong>Probation period</strong> — maximum 6 months under UAE labor law</li>
        <li><strong>Notice period</strong> — standard is 30 days; confirm in both language versions</li>
        <li><strong>Benefits</strong> — housing, transport, medical insurance terms</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- After Work Permit -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>After the Work Permit: What Comes Next</h2>
      <p>The work permit is step one. Here is the full post-approval sequence.</p>

      <div class="next-steps">
        <div class="next-step">
          <span class="next-step-num">1</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Entry Permit</h4>
            <p>If you are outside the UAE, your employer arranges the entry permit (employment visa). Valid for 60 days.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="next-step">
          <span class="next-step-num">2</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Medical Fitness Test</h4>
            <p>Required at a DHA-approved medical center within 60 days of entry. Blood test and chest X-ray.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="next-step">
          <span class="next-step-num">3</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Emirates ID</h4>
            <p>Apply through ICP. Biometrics at a service center. Usually takes 5-7 working days.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="next-step">
          <span class="next-step-num">4</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Residence Visa Stamping</h4>
            <p>Visa stamped in your passport. Then you can open a bank account, get a <a href="/personal/immigration/license/">driving license</a>, and sponsor family members through <a href="/resources/gdrfa-family-visa-documents/">GDRFA</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Need translations for other documents in your employment journey? We handle <a href="/personal/immigration/pcc/">police clearance certificates</a>, <a href="/personal/immigration/bank/">bank statements</a>, and all <a href="/personal/immigration/">immigration documents</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        {faqs.map((faq) => (
          <details class="faq-item" name="mohre-faq">
            <summary>{faq.question}</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer" set:html={faq.answer} />
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA Section -->
  <section class="section bg-dark">
    <div class="container container--narrow" style="text-align: center;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--text-on-dark);">Need Your Documents Translated for MOHRE?</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--text-on-dark-muted); max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto 2rem;">Send your degree, experience letters, or other documents via WhatsApp. We confirm what needs translation, check attestation status, and deliver within 24 hours.</p>
      <a href="https://wa.me/971508620217" class="cta-button">
        <i class="fab fa-whatsapp"></i> Send Documents on WhatsApp
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related Guides -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Related Guides</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="/blog/mohre-work-permit-document-issues/" class="related-card">
          <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
          <h3>MOHRE Rejection Prevention</h3>
